#: ../../../basic/params.rst:9
msgid "Passing parameters to SQL queries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:13
msgid ""
"This way of passing queries has been the \"classic\" way for many years. "
"However, starting from Python 3.14, you might be interested in using the "
"more expressive :ref:`template string queries <template-strings>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:17
msgid ""
"Most of the times, writing a program you will have to mix bits of SQL "
"statements with values provided by the rest of the program:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:20
msgid "SELECT some, fields FROM some_table WHERE id = ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:24
msgid ""
":sql:`id` equals what? Probably you will have a Python value you are looking "
"for."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:29
msgid "`!execute()` arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:31
msgid ""
"Passing parameters to a SQL statement happens in functions such as `Cursor."
"execute()` by using ``%s`` placeholders in the SQL statement, and passing a "
"sequence of values as the second argument of the function. For example the "
"Python function call:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:36
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"\"\"\n"
"    INSERT INTO some_table (id, created_at, last_name)\n"
"    VALUES (%s, %s, %s);\n"
"    \"\"\",\n"
"    (10, datetime.date(2020, 11, 18), \"O'Reilly\"))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:44
msgid "is *roughly* equivalent to the SQL command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:46
msgid ""
"INSERT INTO some_table (id, created_at, last_name)\n"
"VALUES (10, '2020-11-18', 'O''Reilly');"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:51
msgid ""
"Note that the parameters will not be really merged to the query: query and "
"the parameters are sent to the server separately: see :ref:`server-side-"
"binding` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:55
msgid ""
"Named arguments are supported too using :samp:`%({name})s` placeholders in "
"the query and specifying the values into a mapping.  Using named arguments "
"allows to specify the values in any order and to repeat the same value in "
"several places in the query::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:60
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"\"\"\n"
"    INSERT INTO some_table (id, created_at, updated_at, last_name)\n"
"    VALUES (%(id)s, %(created)s, %(created)s, %(name)s);\n"
"    \"\"\",\n"
"    {'id': 10, 'name': \"O'Reilly\", 'created': datetime.date(2020, 11, 18)})"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:66
msgid ""
"Using characters ``%``, ``(``, ``)`` in the argument names is not supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:68
msgid ""
"When parameters are used, in order to include a literal ``%`` in the query "
"you can use the ``%%`` string::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:71
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"SELECT (%s % 2) = 0 AS even\", (10,))       # WRONG\n"
"cur.execute(\"SELECT (%s %% 2) = 0 AS even\", (10,))      # correct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:74
msgid ""
"While the mechanism resembles regular Python strings manipulation, there are "
"a few subtle differences you should care about when passing parameters to a "
"query."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:78
msgid ""
"The Python string operator ``%`` *must not be used*: the `~cursor.execute()` "
"method accepts a tuple or dictionary of values as second parameter. |sql-"
"warn|__:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:85
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO numbers VALUES (%s, %s)\" % (10, 20)) # WRONG\n"
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO numbers VALUES (%s, %s)\", (10, 20))  # correct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:92
msgid ""
"For positional variables binding, *the second argument must always be a "
"sequence*, even if it contains a single variable (remember that Python "
"requires a comma to create a single element tuple)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:96
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s)\", \"bar\")    # WRONG\n"
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s)\", (\"bar\"))  # WRONG\n"
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s)\", (\"bar\",)) # correct\n"
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO foo VALUES (%s)\", [\"bar\"])  # correct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:101
msgid "The placeholder *must not be quoted*::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:103
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO numbers VALUES ('%s')\", (\"Hello\",)) # WRONG\n"
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO numbers VALUES (%s)\", (\"Hello\",))   # correct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:106
msgid ""
"The variables placeholder *must always be a* ``%s``, even if a different "
"placeholder (such as a ``%d`` for integers or ``%f`` for floats) may look "
"more appropriate for the type. You may find other placeholders used in "
"Psycopg queries (``%b`` and ``%t``) but they are not related to the type of "
"the argument: see :ref:`binary-data` if you want to read more::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:112
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO numbers VALUES (%d)\", (10,))   # WRONG\n"
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO numbers VALUES (%s)\", (10,))   # correct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:115
msgid ""
"Only query values should be bound via this method: it shouldn't be used to "
"merge table or field names to the query. If you need to generate SQL queries "
"dynamically (for instance choosing a table name at runtime) you can use the "
"functionalities provided in the `psycopg.sql` module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:120
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO %s VALUES (%s)\", ('numbers', 10))  # WRONG\n"
"cur.execute(                                                # correct\n"
"    SQL(\"INSERT INTO {} VALUES (%s)\").format(Identifier('numbers')),\n"
"    (10,))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:131
msgid "Danger: SQL injection"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:133
msgid ""
"The SQL representation of many data types is often different from their "
"Python string representation. The typical example is with single quotes in "
"strings: in SQL single quotes are used as string literal delimiters, so the "
"ones appearing inside the string itself must be escaped, whereas in Python "
"single quotes can be left unescaped if the string is delimited by double "
"quotes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:139
msgid ""
"Because of the difference, sometimes subtle, between the data types "
"representations, a naïve approach to query strings composition, such as "
"using Python strings concatenation, is a recipe for *terrible* problems::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:143
msgid ""
"SQL = \"INSERT INTO authors (name) VALUES ('%s')\" # NEVER DO THIS\n"
"data = (\"O'Reilly\", )\n"
"cur.execute(SQL % data) # THIS WILL FAIL MISERABLY\n"
"# SyntaxError: syntax error at or near \"Reilly\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:148
msgid ""
"If the variables containing the data to send to the database come from an "
"untrusted source (such as data coming from a form on a web site) an attacker "
"could easily craft a malformed string, either gaining access to unauthorized "
"data or performing destructive operations on the database. This form of "
"attack is called `SQL injection`_ and is known to be one of the most "
"widespread forms of attack on database systems. Before continuing, please "
"print `this page`__ as a memo and hang it onto your desk."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:159
msgid ""
"Psycopg can :ref:`automatically convert Python objects to SQL values<types-"
"adaptation>`: using this feature your code will be more robust and reliable. "
"We must stress this point:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:165
msgid ""
"Don't manually merge values to a query: hackers from a foreign country will "
"break into your computer and steal not only your disks, but also your cds, "
"leaving you only with the three most embarrassing records you ever bought. "
"On cassette tapes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:170
msgid ""
"If you use the ``%`` operator to merge values to a query, con artists will "
"seduce your cat, who will run away taking your credit card and your "
"sunglasses with them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:174
msgid ""
"If you use ``+`` to merge a textual value to a string, bad guys in balaclava "
"will find their way to your fridge, drink all your beer, and leave your "
"toilet seat up and your toilet paper in the wrong orientation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:178
msgid ""
"You don't want to manually merge values to a query: :ref:`use the provided "
"methods <query-parameters>` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:181
msgid ""
"The correct way to pass variables in a SQL command is using the second "
"argument of the `Cursor.execute()` method::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:184
msgid ""
"SQL = \"INSERT INTO authors (name) VALUES (%s)\"  # Note: no quotes\n"
"data = (\"O'Reilly\", )\n"
"cur.execute(SQL, data)  # Note: no % operator"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:190
msgid ""
"Python static code checkers are not quite there yet, but, in the future, it "
"will be possible to check your code for improper use of string expressions "
"in queries. See :ref:`literal-string` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:196
msgid ""
"Now that you know how to pass parameters to queries, you can take a look at :"
"ref:`how Psycopg converts data types <types-adaptation>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:206
msgid "Binary parameters and results"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:208
msgid ""
"PostgreSQL has two different ways to transmit data between client and "
"server: `~psycopg.pq.Format.TEXT`, always available, and `~psycopg.pq.Format."
"BINARY`, available most of the times but not always. Usually the binary "
"format is more efficient to use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:213
msgid ""
"Psycopg can support both formats for each data type. Whenever a value is "
"passed to a query using the normal ``%s`` placeholder, the best format "
"available is chosen (often, but not always, the binary format is picked as "
"the best choice)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:218
msgid ""
"If you have a reason to select explicitly the binary format or the text "
"format for a value you can use respectively a ``%b`` placeholder or a ``%t`` "
"placeholder instead of the normal ``%s``. `~Cursor.execute()` will fail if a "
"`~psycopg.adapt.Dumper` for the right data type and format is not available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:223
msgid ""
"The same two formats, text or binary, are used by PostgreSQL to return data "
"from a query to the client. Unlike with parameters, where you can choose the "
"format value-by-value, all the columns returned by a query will have the "
"same format. Every type returned by the query should have a `~psycopg.adapt."
"Loader` configured, otherwise the data will be returned as unparsed `!str` "
"(for text results) or buffer (for binary results)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:231
msgid ""
"The `pg_type`_ table defines which format is supported for each PostgreSQL "
"data type. Text input/output is managed by the functions declared in the "
"``typinput`` and ``typoutput`` fields (always present), binary input/output "
"is managed by the ``typsend`` and ``typreceive`` (which are optional)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:239
msgid ""
"Because not every PostgreSQL type supports binary output, by default, the "
"data will be returned in text format. In order to return data in binary "
"format you can create the cursor using `Connection.cursor`\\ `!"
"(binary=True)` or execute the query using `Cursor.execute`\\ `!"
"(binary=True)`. A case in which requesting binary results is a clear winner "
"is when you have large binary data in the database, such as images::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:246
msgid ""
"cur.execute(\n"
"    \"SELECT image_data FROM images WHERE id = %s\", [image_id], "
"binary=True)\n"
"data = cur.fetchone()[0]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../basic/params.rst:252
msgid ""
"You cannot execute :ref:`multiple statements in the same query <multi-"
"statements>` when requesting a binary result."
msgstr ""

